            "content": "# PR #10048 — Cross-Verification of Review Findings\n\n## C1: Schema backward compatibility — `autonomyLevel` field type change\n**REAL, but mitigated in practice.**\n\nThe old `SessionSettingsSchema` had `autonomyLevel: z.nativeEnum(AutonomyMode)` (required). The new schema has `autonomyLevel: z.nativeEnum(AutonomyLevel).optional()`. An old CLI responding with `autonomyLevel: 'normal'` will fail Zod parse because `'normal'` is not in `AutonomyLevel` (`off|low|medium|high`). `.optional()` allows the field to be missing, but NOT to be an invalid value.\n\nThe parse happens in two places:\n- `daemon-core/droid-request-handler.ts:1063` (daemon parsing CLI response)\n- `droid-sdk/client.ts:237` (SDK client parsing daemon response)\n\n**Mitigation**: Daemon and CLI are bundled together in the same monorepo deploy. The web frontend doesn't use `droid-sdk` (daemon-core does). So cross-version skew between daemon↔CLI is unlikely in practice. **Medium risk, not Critical**, unless desktop app auto-updates daemon independently from CLI.\n\n## M1: `ProceedAutoRun*` and `ProceedOnce` paths still use `setAutonomyMode()`\n**REAL.** Confirmed at `tool-confirmation.ts` lines 389 and 412. `ProceedAutoRunLow/Medium/High` calls `getSessionController().setAutonomyMode(newMode)` and `ProceedOnce` + ExitSpecMode calls `setAutonomyMode(AutonomyMode.Normal)`. Meanwhile, `ProceedAlways` at line 333 correctly uses `setAutonomyLevel()`. Inconsistent migration -- functionally correct (legacy method still works) but will need cleanup.\n\n## M2: Missing error handling in V1.1 `onLevelChange`/`onSpecModeChange`\n**REAL.** At `DroidSessionChat.tsx` lines 1205-1222, both callbacks do `await onUpdateInteractionSettings(...)` without try/catch. The old `handleAutonomyModeChange` wrapper had try/catch + `logException` + `onError` callback. A rejected promise will propagate as unhandled. The caller (`ActiveSession.module.tsx`) passes `useActiveSessionSettings().updateInteractionSettings` which does have internal error handling (catches and rolls back), but if the catch itself throws or if a different caller doesn't handle errors, it'll be unhandled.\n\n**Nuance**: `useActiveSessionSettings.updateInteractionSettings` already wraps the daemon call in try/catch with rollback. So in practice the promise won't reject. But the component shouldn't assume that about its callback prop. **Real but low practical risk.**\n\n## M3: Inconsistent default `autonomyLevel` — `Low` vs `Off`\n**REAL.** `SessionDetail.page.tsx` line 269: `rawInitialSettings.autonomyLevel ?? AutonomyLevel.Low`. Everywhere else (`resolveInteractionSettings`, `useActiveSessionSettings`, `SessionStore`, `DroidSessionChat`) defaults to `AutonomyLevel.Off`. This preserves the pre-PR behavior (old code had `AutonomyMode.AutoLow` which maps to `Low`), but creates an inconsistency where the active session entry point defaults differently from new session and hook defaults.\n\n## M4: Dead `autonomyMode` passthrough in `ActiveSession.module.tsx`\n**REAL.** Line 325: `autonomyMode: initialSettings?.autonomyMode` is passed to `useActiveSessionSettings` via `initialSettings`, but the hook (lines 86-87) only reads `initialSettings.interactionMode` and `initialSettings.autonomyLevel`. The `autonomyMode` field is carried through but never consumed. Dead code.\n\n## M5: `useActiveSessionSettings` ignores `autonomyMode` from `initialSettings`\n**REAL — same issue as M4**, viewed from the consumer side. The hook accepts `RawInitialSettings` which includes `autonomyMode?`, but only reads `interactionMode` and `autonomyLevel`. If a caller provided ONLY `autonomyMode` without decoupled fields, the hook would silently fall back to defaults. All current callers provide decoupled fields, so this is not a live bug, but the type contract is misleading.\n\n**Note**: M4 and M5 are the same underlying issue (dead passthrough + ignored field). Should be consolidated into one finding.\n\n## M6: `SessionSettings.interactionMode`/`autonomyLevel` typed as optional but always populated\n**REAL.** `SessionController.ts` interface at line 62-63 has `interactionMode?: DroidInteractionMode; autonomyLevel?: AutonomyLevel`. But `getSettings()` at line 204-205 always populates them from `getCurrentModeState()` which derives from `ModeService` (always has values). The optional typing forces callers to do unnecessary undefined checks. However, this is a pre-existing pattern in the CLI codebase (other fields like `specModeModelId` are also optional). **Real but low impact -- consistent with surrounding code.**\n\n## M7: `outcome` field optional in `AgentEventPayloads[PermissionResponse]`\n**REAL.** `AgentEventBus.ts` line 226: `outcome?: ToolConfirmationOutcome`. Every emit site now provides `outcome` (verified in the adapter and handler). Making it required would be cleaner, but the optional typing doesn't cause bugs -- the handler has fallback logic to infer outcome from `approvedToolIds.length`. **Real but low impact.**\n\n## M8: `SessionDefaultSettingsSchema` not migrated\n**PARTIALLY REAL.** The schema at `packages/common/src/settings/schema.ts` line 22 still only has `autonomyMode`. However, it ALSO has `interactionMode` (line 26). So the schema already has decoupled fields! The issue is that the enterprise controls form reads `sessionDefaultSettings.autonomyMode` and converts, rather than reading `interactionMode`/`autonomyLevel` directly. The form writes back as `autonomyMode` for backward compat.\n\n**Re-evaluation**: The schema already supports decoupled fields (`interactionMode` at line 26), but `autonomyLevel` as an `AutonomyLevel` type is NOT present in this schema (only `autonomyMode` as `AutonomyMode`). The enterprise controls translation layer is still needed. **Real but lower severity -- the schema is partially migrated.**\n\n## M9: Duplicate commits in history\n**REAL.** 14 commits, with clear duplicates:\n- `7c0415fce3` and `41d2285fef` (same message)\n- `311fa70020